In React, the `useMemo` function is a hook that allows you to memoize a value so that it's not recalculated on every render. Here's an example of how you can use it:

```jsx
import React, { useMemo } from 'react';

function MyComponent({ data }) {
  const memoizedData = useMemo(() => {
    // Here you can put any function that returns a value
    // The value will be recalculated only when the dependencies change
    return data.map(item => item * 2);
  }, [data]);

  return (
    <div>
      {memoizedData.map(item => (
        <div key={item}>{item}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this example, `memoizedData` is a value that's calculated based on the `data` prop. The `useMemo` function takes two arguments: a function that returns the value, and an array of dependencies. In this case, we're passing `data` as the dependency.

When the `data` prop changes, the function inside `useMemo` will be called again, and the new value will be memoized.

